  "prompt": "How can I recover deleted photos from app lock new version?",
  "response": "Recovering deleted photos from an app lock (like AppLock by DoMobile Lab or similar) can be tricky because the app itself doesn't typically have a \"recycle bin\" or dedicated recovery feature. The success of your recovery depends on how the photos were deleted, where they were stored, and whether you have backups. Here's a breakdown of possible scenarios and solutions:\n\n**Understanding How App Locks Work (And How Photos Are Affected)**\n\n*   **App Locks Primarily Lock Apps:**  Most app locks don't directly manage or modify your photos. They only prevent unauthorized access to apps that *contain* your photos (like Gallery, Google Photos, or file managers).\n*   **Where Were the Photos Stored?:**  Knowing where the photos were *originally* stored is crucial.  Common locations include:\n    *   **Internal Storage (DCIM folder, Downloads folder, etc.):**  This is the phone's main storage.\n    *   **SD Card:** External memory card.\n    *   **Cloud Storage (Google Photos, Dropbox, etc.):** Photos are backed up online.\n\n**Recovery Options**\n\n1.  **Check Cloud Backup Services (Most Likely Solution if you used them):**\n\n    *   **Google Photos:** If you used Google Photos and had \"Backup and Sync\" enabled, the deleted photos are likely in your Google Photos \"Trash\" or \"Bin.\"  You have 60 days to restore them.\n        *   Open Google Photos on your phone or computer.\n        *   Go to the \"Library\" tab.\n        *   Tap \"Trash\" (or \"Bin\").\n        *   Select the photos you want to recover and tap \"Restore.\"\n    *   **Other Cloud Services (Dropbox, OneDrive, etc.):**  Check the trash/deleted items folder within the specific cloud storage app or website.  They usually have a similar recovery mechanism.\n\n2.  **Check the \"App Lock Vault\" (If it Exists):**\n\n    *   *Some* app locks have a built-in feature to hide photos within a secure vault.  If you moved photos into this vault *within* the App Lock app, and then deleted them *from the vault*, look for a recovery option *within* the app lock itself.\n    *   **Open the App Lock App:** Authenticate yourself.\n    *   **Look for a Vault/Hide Photos Section:**  The name varies depending on the app.\n    *   **Check for a \"Trash,\" \"Recently Deleted,\" or \"Restore\" Option:**  Explore the settings within the vault.\n    *   **Important Note:**  If you uninstalled the App Lock app *without* first restoring photos from its vault, those photos are likely permanently lost.\n\n3.  **Data Recovery Software (For Internal Storage/SD Card - Less Likely to be Successful, Requires a Computer):**\n\n    *   If the photos were stored on your phone's internal storage or SD card and not backed up, you *might* be able to recover them using data recovery software. **This is a long shot, and the chances of success decrease with time and device usage after deletion.** The more you use your phone after deleting the photos, the higher the chance that the sectors where the photos were stored have been overwritten with new data.\n    *   **Important Considerations:**\n        *   **Stop Using Your Phone Immediately:** The more you use your phone after deleting the photos, the lower your chances of recovery.  Avoid taking new photos, downloading files, or installing apps.\n        *   **Rooting:** Many Android data recovery tools require you to \"root\" your phone. Rooting voids your warranty and can be risky.  Only do this if you are comfortable with the process and understand the risks.\n        *   **Computer Required:**  You will need a computer (Windows or Mac) to run the data recovery software.\n    *   **Popular Data Recovery Software Options (For Android):**\n        *   **EaseUS MobiSaver for Android:**  A popular commercial option.\n        *   **Dr.Fone - Data Recovery (Android):** Another widely used commercial tool.\n        *   **Recuva (For Windows):**  A general data recovery tool that *might* work if you connect your phone in mass storage mode (less likely on modern Android).\n    *   **How to Use Data Recovery Software (General Steps):**\n        1.  **Download and Install the Software:**  On your computer.\n        2.  **Enable USB Debugging:**  On your Android phone:\n            *   Go to Settings > About Phone (or About Device).\n            *   Find \"Build Number\" and tap it repeatedly (usually 7 times) until you see \"You are now a developer!\"\n            *   Go back to Settings > Developer Options.\n            *   Enable \"USB Debugging.\"  (You might need to connect your phone to your computer first).\n        3.  **Connect Your Phone to Your Computer:**  Using a USB cable.  Choose \"Media Transfer Protocol (MTP)\" or \"File Transfer\" if prompted.\n        4.  **Run the Data Recovery Software:**  Follow the software's instructions to scan your phone's storage.\n        5.  **Select and Recover Photos:**  The software will display a list of recoverable files.  Look for your deleted photos and select them to recover.  Save the recovered photos to a folder on your computer (not back to your phone).\n\n4.  **Check Your Phone's Gallery \"Recently Deleted\" or \"Trash\" Folder (If Applicable):**\n\n    *   Some phone manufacturers (like Samsung) have a \"Recently Deleted\" or \"Trash\" folder within their default Gallery app.  Deleted photos might be temporarily stored there.\n    *   Open your Gallery app and look for a \"Recently Deleted,\" \"Trash,\" or \"Bin\" option (usually in the menu or settings).\n\n**Important Considerations and Warnings:**\n\n*   **Time is of the Essence:** The sooner you try to recover the photos, the better your chances.\n*   **Avoid Overwriting Data:** Stop using your phone as much as possible.  Don't take new photos, download files, or install apps until you've tried recovery.\n*   **Recovery is Not Guaranteed:** Data recovery software is not always successful.  There's a chance that the photos are permanently lost, especially if they were stored on internal storage and a significant amount of time has passed.\n*   **Beware of Scams:** Be cautious of apps or services that promise guaranteed photo recovery. Many are scams or malware.  Stick to reputable data recovery software.\n*   **Backups are Essential:** The best way to protect your photos is to back them up regularly to a cloud service (Google Photos, Dropbox, etc.) or to your computer.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\n1.  **First, check Google Photos or other cloud backups.** This is the most likely place to find your photos.\n2.  **Then, check the App Lock's vault** for any \"Recently Deleted\" or recovery features.\n3.  **If neither of those work, consider data recovery software as a last resort, but be aware of the risks and limitations.**\n\nGood luck! I hope you are able to recover your photos. Remember that preventing data loss with regular backups is the best approach in the future.\n",
